## 4. Solver mechanics — why RT went up

An unexpected but correct side effect: RT rose from 234 to 301 (+29%)
while CT fell from 354 to 276 (-22%).

**Why:** both RT and CT carry the same excess penalty weight. But the
LC-06 hard minimums differ per month: 4 RT + 2 CT for a full month. On
a full-month partition:
- First 4 RT per resource: `excess_rt = 0`, cost = 0
- First 2 CT per resource: `excess_ct = 0`, cost = 0
- 5th RT: `excess_rt = 1`, cost = 50
- 3rd CT: `excess_ct = 1`, cost = 50

When the solver needs a rest day (e.g. for LC-05 weekend coupling), it
**prefers RT first** because "free slots" are available up to the 4 RT
minimum before excess kicks in, whereas CT has only 2 free slots. This
is a rational, unforced rebalancing — not a bug.

**Distribution check vs static targets** (49 resources × 2 segments ≈
49 full-month-equivalent):
- RT static target: 4/month × 49 × ~1.1 months = ~216. R4: 301 (39% over, mostly in full-month partitions)
- CT static target: 2/month × 49 × ~1.1 months = ~108. R4: 276 (156% over, but 51% improvement on the zero-target case)

The CT excess is now ~168 units × weight 50 = ~8,400 cost in the
objective. The RT excess is ~85 units × 50 = ~4,250. Total ~12,650 in
excess penalty — consistent with the ~4,600 objective_value jump vs
R3 (the rest was offset by the solver finding tighter solutions
elsewhere).

